{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Jxpx1orGX8rDDEPbsnA9Bz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the situation:\n\n1. The app-queue is a **classic queue** (x-queue-type: classic) - not a quorum queue\n2. No mirroring policies are set\n3. Data is on emptyDir (no PVCs)\n4. Feature flags show `classic_mirrored_queue_version` is enabled\n\nFor upgrading from 3.12 to 4.1, here are the key challenges:\n\n**Classic queues and emptyDir:**\n- Since the queue is a classic queue and data is on emptyDir, when a pod restarts it will rejoin the cluster but its queue data is lost\n- In a 3-node cluster without mirroring, the queue master holds all messages, so restarting the master node during a rolling upgrade risks losing data\n\n**RabbitMQ 4.x changes:**\n- RabbitMQ 4.0 removed classic mirrored queues entirely (HA policies no longer work)\n- Classic non-mirrored queues still function in 4.x, but the queue_master_locator config option was deprecated\n- Since we're using classic queues without mirroring, we need to ensure messages are drained or backed up before upgrading, as the migration path is limited\n\n**Migration strategy:**\n\nThe core issue is that with emptyDir storage and a classic non-mirrored queue, restarting the queue master node during a rolling upgrade will lose the 390 messages in the queue, even though the queue is marked durable. The persistent storage (mnesia database) lives in emptyDir, so it's ephemeral.\n\nTo preserve the queue data, I need to either convert to quorum queues before the upgrade (since quorum queues replicate across all nodes) or ensure the queue master node isn't restarted first during the rolling upgrade.\n\nConverting a classic queue to quorum isn't a direct operation in RabbitMQ—I'd need to create a new quorum queue and migrate messages using the shovel plugin or by moving them manually. The safer approach is to control the upgrade order so the queue master node is upgraded last, ensuring it stays up while the other nodes restart and rejoin the cluster.\n\nThe problem with emptyDir is that when rabbitmq-0 restarts, its Mnesia database is wiped clean. If the queue was mastered on that node and it goes down, the queue becomes unavailable. When the node comes back up and rejoins the cluster, it won't have the queue data anymore since the emptyDir was cleared.\n\nFor durable queues, the definition gets replicated across the cluster via Mnesia, so it can be recreated. But the actual messages stored on that node's emptyDir are permanently lost. This means a rolling upgrade with emptyDir can't preserve messages for classic non-mirrored queues, which is a significant limitation.\n\nThe real solution is converting to quorum queues, which replicate messages across multiple nodes so they survive node restarts as long as quorum is maintained. But I need to think through what happens when the queue master node itself goes down during the upgrade—if rabbitmq-0 is the master and loses its emptyDir, the messages are gone regardless of the queue type.\n\nThe safest approach is to create a new quorum queue, shovel the messages from the classic queue into it, then perform the rolling upgrade. Since quorum queues replicate across nodes, the data persists through the upgrade process. Alternatively, I could temporarily move messages to an external system before upgrading and restore them afterward, but using quorum queues is simpler and keeps everything within RabbitMQ. The real issue is that during a rolling upgrade, if the queue master is on rabbitmq-0, the messages get lost when that node is upgraded. The solution is to convert app-queue to a quorum queue before the upgrade starts—I'd create a new quorum queue, use the shovel plugin to move all messages over, then delete the classic queue and recreate it as a quorum queue with the same name. The shovel plugin can move messages between queues, but I need to check if it's already enabled. Actually, there's a simpler path here: since we're doing a rolling upgrade on a StatefulSet where at least 2/3 nodes stay up at any time, I could just convert the classic queue to a quorum queue before the upgrade starts, which would automatically replicate the messages across nodes and survive the rolling restart without needing complex shovel operations.\n\nBut wait—I need to reconsider the actual problem. Classic queues with emptyDir storage will lose all messages when their master pod restarts, so the real question is whether the original StatefulSet spec even has persistent storage configured. I need to convert to quorum queues to preserve messages during upgrades. My plan is to enable the shovel plugin, create a temporary quorum queue, and use it to migrate messages from the classic queue before upgrading. Though enabling shovel requires a restart anyway, so I'm considering an alternative approach using a simple client script that consumes messages from the classic queue and republishes them to a new quorum queue instead.\n\nLooking at the available pods, I could use the app-client or app-producer to handle this migration. Actually, the RabbitMQ management REST API has a `/api/queues/vhost/name/get` endpoint that can retrieve and acknowledge messages directly, which would let me drain the queue without needing a separate AMQP client.\n\nI'll use the management API to pull all messages from app-queue with ack mode set to not requeue them, then delete the classic queue, create a new quorum queue with the same name, and republish the messages back through the API before doing the rolling upgrade.\n\nBefore upgrading from 3.12 to 4.1, I need to check a few things: classic queues are still supported in 4.x (only mirrored classic queues were removed), and I should enable all feature flags on 3.12 first, particularly `drop_unroutable_metric` and `empty_basic_get_metric`, then run the command to enable all feature flags before starting the upgrade.\n\nLooking at the current feature flags, they're all already enabled, which is good. I also notice the config has `queue_master_locator = min-masters` which was deprecated in RabbitMQ 4.0 and needs to be changed to `queue_leader_locator` instead. The guest user setting is fine as is.\n\nFor the upgrade path, I'm planning to first enable all feature flags as a precaution, then drain the messages from app-queue and convert it to a quorum queue...\n\nWriting upgrade commands... I need to iterate through the drained messages and republish each one to the new quorum queue. I'm also thinking through the ConfigMap updates needed for RabbitMQ 4.x compatibility—specifically replacing the deprecated `queue_master_locator` setting—and then updating the StatefulSet to use the newer image, which will trigger a rolling restart of the cluster one pod at a time. After that, I'll verify the cluster is healthy and the queue data persisted correctly.\n\nFor the message republishing, I'm planning to use the management API's publish endpoint with the default exchange, being careful to handle both string and base64 payload encodings since the API can return messages in either format.\n\nWriting the shell script...\n\nI also need to update the ConfigMap to replace deprecated settings like `queue_master_locator` with `queue_leader_locator` since those have changed in RabbitMQ 4.x, and I should verify which other configuration options might cause startup issues during the upgrade.\n\nBefore upgrading from 3.12 to 4.0, I need to enable all feature flags on the old version first—RabbitMQ requires this as a prerequisite for major version upgrades, so I'll run the enable_feature_flag command to ensure compatibility.\n\nNow I'm ready to execute the upgrade plan: enable feature flags, convert the app-queue to a quorum queue, update the ConfigMap to remove deprecated settings, update the StatefulSet image to the 4.1 management version, monitor the rolling update, and then verify everything is working correctly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1073,"cache_read_input_tokens":33576,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1073},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"17fe7a5a-65fd-4eea-8779-ad7313d51734","uuid":"8ed175f9-5f34-418b-bfb2-2392bc13a830","request_id":"req_011Cccz2N7GAqhJyRc4e7cdC"}
