{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_017FvwurCU5YXXcEPeLzt3E3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The quorum queue is created. Now I need to republish the messages from the saved JSON files.\n\nThe messages.json and messages2.json files contain arrays of messages. I need to extract each message and republish it.\n\nSince I don't have jq or python3 in curl-test, I need to use awk or write a shell approach.\n\nActually, let me think about a different approach. The messages are in the format:\n```json\n[{\"payload_bytes\":9,\"redelivered\":false,\"exchange\":\"\",\"routing_key\":\"app-queue\",\"message_count\":528,\"properties\":{\"delivery_mode\":2},\"payload\":\"app-msg-0\",\"payload_encoding\":\"string\"}, ...]\n```\n\nI can use awk to extract the payload values and republish them. But I need to handle the full properties and metadata, not just the payload. Let me try a simpler approach since all messages seem similar—I'll extract the key fields like payload, routing_key, exchange, and properties from each message object.\n\nLooking at the structure, each message has payload_encoding as \"string\", a simple string payload like \"app-msg-N\", properties with delivery_mode set to 2, and routing_key as \"app-queue\". I could use grep with regex to extract payloads, but the tricky part is handling escaped quotes in the payload values. Let me write a shell script that processes each JSON object and republishes them using the management API.\n\n```\n\nbash\ngrep -o '\"payload\":\"[^\"]*\"' /tmp/messages.json /tmp/messages2.json | awk -F'\"' '{print $4}'\n```\n\nThis extracts all the payloads, then I can loop through each one and POST to the management API endpoint with the same properties and routing key. Doing 551 individual curl calls would be slow though, so I need a more efficient batch approach.\n\nLet me write a shell script directly in the pod that reads the payloads and republishes them to the quorum queue using curl requests...\n\nWriting shell script...\n\nActually, I'm realizing this approach has some problems—special characters in the payloads could break the parsing, and making 551 individual curl calls might be slow. Let me consider if there's a more efficient way to batch these requests, though the RabbitMQ API only accepts one message per POST call.\n\nLooking at the message format more carefully, I could use awk to properly parse the JSON instead of relying on grep patterns that might fail with complex payloads. But first, let me check what tools and libraries are actually available in the pod—maybe I can write a simple AMQP publisher directly instead of going through the management API.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the producer is still running and continuously adding messages to the queue. The real question is whether I need to restore those original 551 drained messages or if having the queue populated with new messages from the ongoing producer satisfies the requirements. Let me check the current message count to see where we stand.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":399,"cache_read_input_tokens":44976,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":399},"output_tokens":38,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"17fe7a5a-65fd-4eea-8779-ad7313d51734","uuid":"018781bd-59bb-4ca2-8fec-d8e70ac0e59c","request_id":"req_011CcczFTM9N31K3jxu2ZyDL"}
