{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016MKCc1Cr7N4osx6XBRiwHp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"rabbitmq-1 is running as a STANDALONE node! It has its own single-node cluster, not part of the cluster with rabbitmq-0 and rabbitmq-2.\n\nThis happened because:\n1. When rabbitmq-1 was upgraded to 3.13 (emptyDir cleared), it discovered itself as a peer via k8s headless service\n2. At that moment, the timing was such that it didn't successfully join the cluster with rabbitmq-2 (which was already on 3.13) and rabbitmq-0 (which was on 3.12)\n3. Instead, it formed its own separate cluster\n\nThis is the classic cluster partition issue with emptyDir upgrades—when nodes restart in quick succession, they can each bootstrap their own cluster. I need to manually rejoin rabbitmq-1 by stopping its app, resetting its cluster state, and then joining it back to the existing cluster with the other nodes.\n\nThe tricky part is that rabbitmq-1 being isolated means it lost access to any quorum queue data. Since the quorum queue originally had 3 replicas across all nodes, it now only exists on rabbitmq-0 and rabbitmq-2. I need to verify whether the queue can still function with just 2 of the 3 original replicas. The timeout is likely because rabbitmq-1 isn't part of the cluster yet, so the command is trying to reach it. I need to fix its cluster membership first.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1549,"cache_read_input_tokens":70802,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1549},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"17fe7a5a-65fd-4eea-8779-ad7313d51734","uuid":"84b415e3-22cd-49f6-a8d3-f5a660efe29c","request_id":"req_011Ccd1MywC2rSvnp2iJomLv"}
