{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NvNKq461EwV58dsLiMFikY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The producer is failing because it's trying to declare the queue with arguments `{\"x-queue-type\":\"classic\",\"x-queue-mode\":\"lazy\"}`. But our restored queue is a quorum queue (`x-queue-type: quorum`).\n\nWhen it tries to declare `app-queue` with `x-queue-type: classic`, RabbitMQ will reject it because the queue already exists with different properties (quorum type). The error is \"Not_Authorized\" but actually looking at the AMQP level, this might be a \"PRECONDITION_FAILED\" error for queue mismatch.\n\nWait, the error was: `app-producer: failed to declare queue in vhost /app: {\"error\":\"not_authorized\",\"reason\":\"Not_Authorized\"}`\nActually, I'm wondering if this is a permissions issue instead. The producer uses `app-user:apppass` which should have permissions on the `/app` vhost, but maybe those permissions weren't set up before the producer first tried to declare the queue. Now that it's restarting after the upgrade, it's still hitting the same failure—either because the queue type mismatch is being reported as \"not_authorized\", or because the permissions are actually missing. The error is actually coming from the HTTP management API, not AMQP—the status code must be 401 or 403 when `app-user` tries to PUT the queue. I need to verify whether `app-user` has the right permissions to access the vhost and declare queues through the management API. they can't authenticate at all, or maybe the credentials aren't being passed correctly. Let me think about whether the issue is with how the curl command is sending the auth header versus the actual permissions setup.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":712,"cache_read_input_tokens":90032,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"epheme