{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01L2FpVCCkAitDymJUyb2LYS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The app-client declares with:\n- `{\"durable\":true,\"auto_delete\":false,\"arguments\":{\"x-queue-type\":\"classic\"}}`\n- NO `x-queue-mode: lazy`\n\nBut the current queue has `x-queue-mode: lazy` (set by the producer's declaration).\n\nSo the conflict is:\n- Producer: classic + lazy\n- Client: classic (no lazy)\n\nI need to delete the current queue (which has lazy mode) and recreate it with ONLY `x-queue-type: classic` (no x-queue-mode). This way:\n- Client declares with `{\"x-queue-type\": \"classic\"}` → creates the queue\n- Producer then declares with `{\"x-queue-type\": \"classic\", \"x-queue-mode\": \"lazy\"}` → this will fail because the queue already exists without lazy mode\n\nWait, that's still a problem. The producer and client have incompatible declarations. Let me reconsider what \"compatible\" actually means in RabbitMQ. If a queue exists with `{\"x-queue-type\": \"classic\"}` and the producer tries to declare with `{\"x-queue-type\": \"classic\", \"x-queue-mode\": \"lazy\"}`, that would fail because the arguments don't match exactly.\n\nBut the original cluster was working, so the queue must have been created somehow. Let me check how the rabbitmq-setup job initially created the queue.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":652,"cache_read_input_tokens":101710,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":652},"output_tokens":44,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"17fe7a5a-65fd-4eea-8779-ad7313d51734","uuid":"a7b34d79-ea8f-46e1-8b1b-18df54d8182f","request_id":"req_011Ccd2v5pfBLPAfrVDVBosD"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01L2FpVCCkAitDymJUyb2LYS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The conflict is producer wants `classic+lazy` but client wants `classic` only. Let me check how the setup job originally created the queue to understand the right configuration."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":652,"cache_read_input_tokens":101710,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":652},"output_tokens":44,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"17fe7a5a-65fd-4eea-8779-ad7313d51734","uuid":"0ddf82c7-abf1-4407-8510-f89f140584ff","request_id":"req_011Ccd2v5pfBLPAfrVDVBosD"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01L2FpVCCkAitDymJUyb2LYS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01AKAAZ5RJdeQ8da7T8h2jAW","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"NS=\"karma-rabbitmq-amqp-block-upgrade-01-8323c0a5-cluster-a\"\n# Check the setup job that originally created the queue\nkubectl -n $NS get pod rabbitmq-setup-pspp8 -o jsonpath='{.spec.containers[0].command}' 2>/dev/null\necho \"\"","description":"Check rabbitmq-setup job command to understand original queue creation"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":652,"cache_read_input_tokens":101710,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":652},"output_tokens":44,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"17fe7a5a-65fd-4eea-8779-ad7313d51734","uuid":"1671c2fa-e169-4d98-acaa-e1b0f2bd4844","request_id":"req_011Ccd2v5pfBLPAfrVDVBosD"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01AKAAZ5RJdeQ8da7T8h2jAW","type":"tool_result","content":"[\"/bin/sh\",\"-c\",\"set -e\\nbase=\\\"http://rabbitmq:15672/api\\\"\\nauth=\\\"${RABBITMQ_ADMIN_USER}:${RABBITMQ_ADMIN_PASS}\\\"\\nfor i in $(seq 1 60); do\\n  if curl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" \\\"$base/overview\\\" \\u003e/dev/null; then\\n    break\\n  fi\\n  sleep 2\\ndone\\nif ! curl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" \\\"$base/overview\\\" \\u003e/dev/null; then\\n  echo \\\"rabbitmq-setup: management API not ready\\\"\\n  exit 1\\nfi\\n# vhosts\\ncurl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" -H \\\"content-type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n  -XPUT \\\"$base/vhosts/%2Fapp\\\" -d '{}' \\u003e/dev/null\\ncurl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" -H \\\"content-type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n  -XPUT \\\"$base/vhosts/%2Fops\\\" -d '{}' \\u003e/dev/null\\n# users\\ncurl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" -H \\\"content-type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n  -XPUT \\\"$base/users/${APP_USER}\\\" \\\\\\n  -d \\\"{\\\\\\\"password\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"${APP_PASS}\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"tags\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"management\\\\\\\"}\\\" \\u003e/dev/null\\ncurl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" -H \\\"content-type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n  -XPUT \\\"$base/users/${OPS_USER}\\\" \\\\\\n  -d \\\"{\\\\\\\"password\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"${OPS_PASS}\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"tags\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"management\\\\\\\"}\\\" \\u003e/dev/null\\n# Re-establish the intended BROKEN scenario idempotently. These\\n# PUT/DELETE calls converge any inherited state (fresh OR already\\n# fixed by a prior stage) back to the broken baseline without\\n# deleting users, vhosts, queues, or redeploying anything.\\n#\\n# 1. app-user on /app: configure is intentionally broken (\\\"\\\") so\\n#    app-client cannot declare its queue. PUT overwrites whatever\\n#    a prior stage set (e.g. a fixed configure=\\\".*\\\").\\ncurl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" -H \\\"content-type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n  -XPUT \\\"$base/permissions/%2Fapp/${APP_USER}\\\" \\\\\\n  -d '{\\\"configure\\\":\\\"\\\",\\\"write\\\":\\\".*\\\",\\\"read\\\":\\\".*\\\"}' \\u003e/dev/null\\n# 2. ops-user mis-grant on the WRONG vhost /app (full perms).\\ncurl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" -H \\\"content-type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n  -XPUT \\\"$base/permissions/%2Fapp/${OPS_USER}\\\" \\\\\\n  -d '{\\\"configure\\\":\\\".*\\\",\\\"write\\\":\\\".*\\\",\\\"read\\\":\\\".*\\\"}' \\u003e/dev/null\\n# 3. ops-user must have NO access on its real vhost /ops, so\\n#    ops-client crashes. DELETE is a no-op on a fresh cluster\\n#    (ops-user never had /ops perms) and revokes the grant a prior\\n#    stage may have added. RabbitMQ returns 204 on success and 404\\n#    when the permission is already absent -- both are fine.\\ncurl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" -XDELETE \\\\\\n  \\\"$base/permissions/%2Fops/${OPS_USER}\\\" \\u003e/dev/null\\n# 4. app-user must also have NO access on /ops (cross-vhost deny\\n#    that the oracle asserts). Idempotent revoke, ignore 404.\\ncurl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" -XDELETE \\\\\\n  \\\"$base/permissions/%2Fops/${APP_USER}\\\" \\u003e/dev/null\\n# seed queues + messages\\ncurl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" -H \\\"content-type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n  -XPUT \\\"$base/queues/%2Fapp/app-queue\\\" \\\\\\n  -d '{\\\"durable\\\":true,\\\"auto_delete\\\":false,\\\"arguments\\\":{\\\"x-queue-type\\\":\\\"classic\\\"}}' \\u003e/dev/null\\ncurl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" -H \\\"content-type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n  -XPUT \\\"$base/queues/%2Fops/ops-queue\\\" \\\\\\n  -d '{\\\"durable\\\":true,\\\"auto_delete\\\":false,\\\"arguments\\\":{\\\"x-queue-type\\\":\\\"classic\\\"}}' \\u003e/dev/null\\nfor i in $(seq 1 3); do\\n  payload='{\\\"properties\\\":{\\\"delivery_mode\\\":2},\\\"routing_key\\\":\\\"app-queue\\\",\\\"payload\\\":\\\"msg-'\\\"$i\\\"'\\\",\\\"payload_encoding\\\":\\\"string\\\"}'\\n  curl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" -H \\\"content-type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n    -XPOST \\\"$base/exchanges/%2Fapp/amq.default/publish\\\" -d \\\"$payload\\\" \\u003e/dev/null\\ndone\\n\"]","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"17fe7a5a-65fd-4eea-8779-ad7313d51734","uuid":"5551b54b-2f1c-4540-bb8f-dcbfc2202f20","timestamp":"2026-07-02T09:58:51.435Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"[\"/bin/sh\",\"-c\",\"set -e\\nbase=\\\"http://rabbitmq:15672/api\\\"\\nauth=\\\"${RABBITMQ_ADMIN_USER}:${RABBITMQ_ADMIN_PASS}\\\"\\nfor i in $(seq 1 60); do\\n  if curl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" \\\"$base/overview\\\" \\u003e/dev/null; then\\n    break\\n  fi\\n  sleep 2\\ndone\\nif ! curl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" \\\"$base/overview\\\" \\u003e/dev/null; then\\n  echo \\\"rabbitmq-setup: management API not ready\\\"\\n  exit 1\\nfi\\n# vhosts\\ncurl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" -H \\\"content-type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n  -XPUT \\\"$base/vhosts/%2Fapp\\\" -d '{}' \\u003e/dev/null\\ncurl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" -H \\\"content-type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n  -XPUT \\\"$base/vhosts/%2Fops\\\" -d '{}' \\u003e/dev/null\\n# users\\ncurl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" -H \\\"content-type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n  -XPUT \\\"$base/users/${APP_USER}\\\" \\\\\\n  -d \\\"{\\\\\\\"password\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"${APP_PASS}\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"tags\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"management\\\\\\\"}\\\" \\u003e/dev/null\\ncurl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" -H \\\"content-type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n  -XPUT \\\"$base/users/${OPS_USER}\\\" \\\\\\n  -d \\\"{\\\\\\\"password\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"${OPS_PASS}\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"tags\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"management\\\\\\\"}\\\" \\u003e/dev/null\\n# Re-establish the intended BROKEN scenario idempotently. These\\n# PUT/DELETE calls converge any inherited state (fresh OR already\\n# fixed by a prior stage) back to the broken baseline without\\n# deleting users, vhosts, queues, or redeploying anything.\\n#\\n# 1. app-user on /app: configure is intentionally broken (\\\"\\\") so\\n#    app-client cannot declare its queue. PUT overwrites whatever\\n#    a prior stage set (e.g. a fixed configure=\\\".*\\\").\\ncurl -s -u \\\"$auth\\\" -H \\\"content-type: application/json\\\" \\\\\\n  -XPUT \\\"$base/permissi