{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Uh9VF2fQKDXerbf1hRAj2s","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me check why app-client is still failing. The queue is now classic without lazy mode. The client should be able to declare it.\n\nOh wait - actually looking at the producer pod: it's Running (12 restarts, last restart 10m ago). But it declared the queue with `x-queue-mode: lazy`. If the queue now exists as plain classic (no lazy), the producer (which tries to declare with lazy mode) should FAIL.\n\nBut the producer IS running! How?\n\nWait, the producer restarted when the queue was lazy, and then... hmm. Actually, the producer declared the queue successfully BEFORE I switched to the non-lazy version. \n\nThen when I deleted and recreated without lazy, the producer is already running (publishing loop) and doesn't try to re-declare. So the producer will keep running as long as it doesn't crash, but the moment it restarts it'll fail trying to declare with lazy mode against a classic queue.\n\nFor app-client, it's stuck in CrashLoopBackOff with 9 restarts. When it comes back up, it'll try to connect to RabbitMQ and declare the queue.\n\nI'm wondering if the app-client has actually restarted yet since I changed the queue to classic, or if it's still waiting for the next backoff cycle to kick in.\n\nLooking at the actual requirements though, the cluster itself is healthy with all three nodes running RabbitMQ 4.1.8, the /app vhost exists, and app-queue has the messages. The app-client being in CrashLoopBackOff is an application-level problem, not a cluster health issue. Let me verify the /ops vhost and ops-queue are also in the right state. The queue declaration should be idempotent since both the client and the existing queue are using the classic type, so it should succeed on the next restart. Let me check the latest logs to see what's actually happening.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"